What would you choose?

He’ll never have the kisses that saved him, he’ll never have the love that crippled him to this broken boy; he’ll never have the happiness but he’ll never have the pain. 

Yoongi doesn’t know if he’d rather remember or forget. +

Yoongi wouldn’t have Jungkook, but then he’d never have him to begin with; he’ll never have this heartbreak over something that wasn’t his to begin with then, he’ll never have the memory of Jungkook haunting him. +

And if Yoongi could go back, turn back the clock, rewind past all the kisses and unfilled promises, go past all the memories Jungkook swore he’d never forget – if he could take it all away and turn his back on Jungkook on that first day – 

Would he? +

If he could go back to the very beginning and erase those first, innocent moments – 

Back before they both knew how much they’d hurt each other, with Yoongi’s love, with Jungkook’s absence of it. +

And if Yoongi could turn back time, if he could miss that first day when he first laid eyes on Jungkook – if he had turned the other way and missed how his smile stood out from the crowd, if Yoongi was just a minute later, never to cross paths. +

How do you forget someone that you love so much? How do you forget a piece of yourself? 

He did. +

But no matter what – no matter what Yoongi wishes for, no matter what he wants – he’ll always want Jungkook more. And he can’t change that, just like how he couldn’t change the fact that Jungkook changed his feelings for him. +

don’t you think he tried, don’t you think he wants to? Don’t you think he wants to /hate/ Jungkook for what he’s done to him? Don’t you think Yoongi wishes he could stop loving him so that he could stop hurting him like this? +

How do you tell someone to stop loving, to stop hurting? 

“It’s best if you moved on.” 

And Yoongi wants to scream, because – +
But how does Yoongi tell his breaking heart to stop crumbling at the thought of Jungkook, how does he tell his crosswire veins to stop carrying the love he has for him? +

Yoongi doesn’t want to believe that it’s nothing now, he doesn’t want to believe he’s diseased; he doesn’t want to be cured of Jungkook, he doesn’t want to love someone that isn’t him. 

Maybe he’s being overdramatic. +

to cry into his pillow and to dream of Jungkook coming back? 

Is it melodramatic – no, is it /foolish/, really – to love Jungkook back? +

And is it melodramatic to be heartbroken? 

To crave him like a drug, for Yoongi to protect himself from the memory of Jungkook like a virus but to succumb to the infection of the happiness he used to bring, to succumb to the loneliness he gives him now; +
It was easier to love Jungkook when he loved Yoongi back. +

It was easier to hold Jungkook in his arms than to let him go, it was easier to say “I love you” to the base of his neck than his retreating figure, it was easier to be the cause of his smile than the reason for his tears. +
Yoongi doesn’t like how the only space Jungkook has in his life now are love-tainted memories that only mock his loneliness without him now. +

And he doesn’t like how Jungkook takes up space in his mind now, how it’s constantly fiddling and wondering where it all went wrong, the heartbreak of trying to figure out where all his love was supposed to go and where Jungkook’s went; +

It was easier then, he thinks. 

None of this messy goodbye, no more pathetic come back; no more shaking fingers hesitant over Jungkook’s number on his phone, no more tossing on his bedsheets and wondering why he left, what Jungkook thought of him now, what changed his mind. +

take it right out of his body before it spreads through to everything he is. 

He doesn’t know which is worse – loving someone who no longer loved you back or not feeling a thing. 

Having a broken heart or none at all. +

And Yoongi’s no doctor, but he thinks Jungkook’s love was a disease that was taking over him, that his days were numbered with him, without him. 

And Yoongi’s no surgeon, but he thinks the only way to treat an infected heart is to cut it out; +

How does he stop himself from seeing Jungkook’s smile on every stranger’s face and saying his name in every new conversation, how does Yoongi stop himself from dreaming of him and waking up lonely; how does he stop himself from loving him,  how does he cure himself of him? +
“How do I stop loving you?” +

for how the world beat him down.  

It’s an infection, Yoongi thinks. It takes over him and he’s this lovesick boy for Jungkook that everyone can see. 

Even after Jungkook’s gone. +

Yoongi doesn’t know how he’s supposed to move on – how he’s supposed to forget the taste of Jungkook’s lips that was the cherry red medicine to his lonely life, how he’s supposed to cure himself of the fingertips tracing his skin that was his physiotherapy to his sore bones +
the constant falling and falling and forgetting what it was like before you were so lovesick, before you were infected by a single touch that spread like disease. +

The visions of the future you believed you could have – no, the /delusions/ – the heart rate pounding much too fast, the sickness that always kept that Cheshire smile on your lips and the restlessness at night; +

Choices.

But of course, Hyunjin couldn’t see it for himself.
He was too busy staring at Jisung.
He was blinded.

Because that’s what led him to believe that he had a chance. It’s what blinded him with the possibility when any rational person could see the indifference in Jisung’s eyes as clearly as they could see the infatuation in Hyunjin’s. +

Hyunjin has always held onto that hope, to that chance that Jisung might love him back; that the beauty of Jisung’s being could love the plain him just like how he loved Jisung. And it’s that hope - the hope that he carried through the darkest nights - that will bring him down. +
Hyunjin doesn’t think of anything except Jisung saying “Yes, I love you too” after years of dreaming of those words leaving his lips. +
He doesn’t think of Jisung and the rumors or his friends and their warnings. +
He doesn’t think of any of those things despite the clear three strikes and the strange absurdity of Jisung’s sudden profession of love towards him. +

But like everything he plays with, he’ll get bored. He’ll get tired of stringing Hyunjin along and he’ll drop him without a warning; already looking for the next new game to play. But Hyunjin doesn’t think of this. +

Hyunjin would come back, over and over again, back to Jisung’s arms and back to the love he harbored for him - you silly, stupid, foolish boy - and Jisung would just break him all over again.

The best toy, really. +

Hyunjin gave him his heart and gave him his head and in doing so, he gave Jisung every opportunity to break him just the way he wanted to. 
And the best part? +
Jisung loved toys and he loved games and Hyunjin’s heart was the toy handed so willingly over to him to take. +

But the thing is, Jisung didn’t need Hyunjin. He wanted Hyunjin. He wanted to play with Hyunjin, to toy with his heart like some plaything that a conniving boy like him would dissect before leaving the pieces lying around as he jumped to his next interest. +

That when Jisung said “I love you”, there wasn’t any sincerity in his voice, in his eyes - he was saying the words that he said to everyone else that caught his eye for more than a minute, and he was using those three words to trap Hyunjin for as long as he needed him. +

That when Jisung touched him, he wasn’t absorbing the love that radiated from Hyunjin’s pores - he was testing the boys’ reaction with calculated brushes of his hand to see just what he could get from him. +

When was he going to see that Jisung didn’t love him?
That when Jisung looked at him, he wasn’t lost in his eyes - he was lost in how he was reflected in them. +

the trouble that would leave Hyunjin crying on the way off the pitch of his game, leaving a trail of his broken heart behind him as he walked into an overwhelming numbness that would last for weeks. +
When was Hyunjin going to see that everything about the boy screamed trouble - and not the exhilarating, thrilling trouble +

Strike Three. +

Hyunjin’s friends coming up to him that day, telling him to be careful with Jisung, advising the boy to forget about him because of who he was now, warning him against loving Jisung in hopes of protecting Hyunjin’s flyaway heart.

Strike Two. +

because the absent phone calls and missing text messages and overall silence on his part meant Hyunjin was the only thing Jisung could think of.

“It’s time you let go.”

No more wishing on starless nights for airplane boys and no more birthday candle cakes that he eats alone; no more 11:11 and wondering about timezones and no more shooting stars and drowning boys clinging onto their lifelines. +

No more distant conversations that make Jungkook’s chest ache, no more goodbyes and rainy days while the sun shines outside; no more running in circles and no more waiting for something that wasn’t meant to be by his side. +

It’s not his fault. It’s not his fault that some things were meant to be just as it’s not Jungkook’s fault that the two of them weren’t one of them.
Yoongi breaks Jungkook’s heart and he swears it’s the last time he’ll ever hurt him. +

Yoongi may have Jungkook’s love but he doesn’t give back the happiness he deserves for it and he knows - Yoongi knows he can’t give it or make it for him; Yoongi, a frantic boy with dirt-stained eyes who was only ever a blemish on Jungkook’s heart that he trusted the elder with.+
In a realization that clogs Jungkook’s throat like dust instead of the acid release of fireworks in his brain when they kiss, he knows it: This is it. +

Try as he might with crooked smiles that Yoongi tries to match; kisses that Jungkook tries to hold on to only to wear them thin and touches that are more like slipping than lingering; Jungkook tried to be happy and Yoongi tried to give that happiness to him, but this is it. +

Too much empty space for all the things neither of them could give each other to fill up the meaning of the word.

And then Jungkook is just left with an almost.
He loves Yoongi and Yoongi loves him back, but it’s just not enough. +

Empty beds and empty eyes, empty promises and empty hearts; maybe it’s Jungkook and maybe it’s Yoongi but the only certainty Jungkook has is that the word ‘Us’ is much too big of a word for the two of them. +

Birthday candles flicker before they fade to smoke and dandelions die for your folly wishes and yet he hasn’t moved on from those things.

But maybe he should after all that he knows. +

“We’ll be infinite.” And Jungkook holds on to them all like his helium balloon dreams that he let himself get carried away in. Jungkook must know by now that shooting stars are merely crashing rocks and 11:11 is just a minute in an endless timeline. +
Jungkook’s moved on - no, no that’s not quite right. Jungkook hasn’t moved on, not from those shooting star, 11:11, birthday candle, dandelion wisp dreams of all he thought Yoongi could’ve been. +

There’s always something missing.
There’s always a gap between the two of them, a space when Yoongi reaches out for Jungkook - he finds his form in the bed but he might as well be passing through a ghost for all he can bring, for all Jungkook can give. +

He holds on to Jungkook like a lifeline but the younger is holding onto him like a daisy petal wish; something with beautiful potential for dreams that you have to let go of for the reality of bigger things. Something Yoongi has to hold on to, to survive. +
He can’t make him happy when he’s a thousand miles away, he can barely make Jungkook happy when he’s by his side. +

Because every ‘I love you’ was followed by an ‘I miss you’; love was never in Jungkook’s arms long enough before it had to fly or drive away, turning into loneliness instead of the bliss it was meant to be.

And Yoongi knows, he knows - he sees that he can’t make Jungkook happy.+

There’s love in broken connections and jetlagged eyes, there’s love in a  promise of ‘I’ll come back’ and there’s love in a goodbye.

There may be love, but that doesn’t disguise the fact that pain is the feeling that such love was coated in. +

Can you call it love when you’re never happy?

There’s love in the telephone lines that curl for thousands of miles from Jungkook to him for months at a time. There’s love in the candid pictures Jungkook ignores for the ones of the two of them on their phones. +

He knows.
Yoongi knows that Jungkook’s heart isn’t in it, that his smiles were only glass reflections of the ones Yoongi gave him; attempts to love Yoongi as much as he loved the younger.
And maybe Jungkook did love him, but it wasn’t ever right. +

The words that had never had meaning until Jimin said them to him. 

“I love you, too.”

The words were almost lost in the quiet of the night. Their two bodies pressed against one another under the sheets that were failing to rival the heat Yoongi felt overflowing in his heart as he finally spoke the words that had been occupying his every thought for so long. +
“I love you,” he hears the words spoken softly. +

That’s what he is to Yoongi. 
Someone who opened his tranquil eyes, something that was surely too good for him, something that he’s certain only comes once every nine lifetimes. 
Something that makes him believe in something he always doubted. +

- 

Jimin is a miracle. 
A /miracle/. 
There’s no other word for it. 
Something undefined, something more than anything that’s ever existed to Yoongi; something so grand and unexplainable that all he had was an open-mouthed word of wonderment with wide eyes. +

For the first time, he felt it – he fell into it. 
Jimin showed him into his own mind through the galaxy in his eyes – beautifully terrifying things that scared Yoongi because of how strangely ethereal it all is.  
Like how much Jimin loved him back. +

Daydreams on early morning sunlit beds and doodles in lined margins, mind spinning in a different way of colors reflecting in the rain and movements in silvery moonlight shadows instead of diagrams and graphs on what love was like to him. +

Did he ever really / think/  before Jimin? 
Think beyond what was before himself, think about all the  ’what-ifs’  without crossing them off and diving straight into them instead +

He showed Yoongi how things aren’t just equations that he can drop in order to move on to the next once he found the answer; some things were /more/, things that were meant to live in his head, in thoughts that he’d turn over when he can’t sleep. +
Jimin showed him how things were a mess of crumpled corners on lonely nights and spinning on rooftop sunsets, how things were / unexplainable/. +

Until he showed Yoongi that numbers couldn’t even touch  the spectrum of all the things he could show him in love, in unknowns. Variables that the alphabet can’t represent, factors he couldn’t simplify +

- 
Did it all ever matter before? 
All the things his pretty little mind used to store – they didn’t have a  meaning  to them until Jimin gave it to him. +

Things that he won’t ever have the word for and letters traced on his arms that don’t spell a thing but hold all the meaning in the world. 
He’s not a believer – but for Jimin, for /him/  
Yoongi could believe in finding a meaning instead of an answer. +

And he knows now, some things you just can’t prove. 
He knows that there are some things he can’t measure or phrase, there are some things like early Sunday mornings with sheets wrapped around his calves that are wrapped around Jimin’s. +

Yoongi was always afraid of falling – building bridges, calculated steps, and hesitant breaths – but Jimin takes it all away with bashful pink lips that breathe in a little something called  faith that he would’ve scoffed at before. +
until Jimin taught him that leaping wasn’t foolish if he landed into his arms. +

Until he told Yoongi stories that he could believe existed when they came woven out of the younger’s lips and mirrored in his eyes. Until he showed Yoongi how a kiss was more than just two mouths with a deeper feeling to it +

/Belief/  was for people who didn’t have enough to build a bridge so they chose to leap instead. 
A little foolish, Yoongi used to think. 
But that was until he met him. +

-
 
Yoongi doesn’t think he’s ever believed in anything until he met Jimin. 
Always a skeptic, always needing cold, hard proof – data in neatly recorded sheets and equal signs to equation lines. +
Jimin tells him it’s his best work. +

Love was science, a set formula to which Yoongi had always tried to input different values into the variables to get the answer he was looking for. 
He had been trying to see how Jimin fits into his equation, but he finds himself doodling in the margins instead. +

If Yoongi was the chemist then he was the existentialist, always questioning the constellations in the night sky that Yoongi measured the distance to for him, formulating ways to build a rocket to fetch a star to match the ones in his eyes. +

All Yoongi needed was a blank whiteboard and he could spell out in formulas and theories just /why/ he loved Jimin so much. 

But Jimin never really did care much for calculations or metaphors +

the reflection of light in Jimin’s eyes when he looks at Yoongi triggers an icy waterfall to his very core. 

It’s science, it’s all science. 
No beautiful words, no paint-splattered canvas of faded violet and gentle turquoise +

Yoongi is drawn to him and it’s pure /magnetism/; how Jimin is his ‘north’ that always points him back home to his arms; electricity in the static of Jimin’s skin against his own and the radiation of heat from his mouth on Yoongi’s neck +

from soft fingertips; he’s the biology of human nature with expanding and contracting lungs breathing in Jimin and heart pulses that are just as erratic as a drug addict and Yoongi’s poison of choice was the chemicals only Jimin could release through a simple touch of his lips. +

/Dopamine/ is what he gives Yoongi, which makes him feel like he’s on a high when the younger touches his skin.  
Poets call it love, but Yoongi is a biological creation of rushing veins, of blood flowing to his cheeks when Jimin says something sweet and goosebump trails +

It’s all chemistry, it’s all biology, it’s all physics.  
It’s the hormones that spike up in his mind whenever he sees him, how there’s a switch in his brain that turns on from the sparks in his cells that light up at the very thought of Jimin+

It’s science. 
That’s the conclusion Yoongi is able to come to in his desperate search for rationality fueled by his denial.
No metaphors for summer rain  or colorful pictures of flowers after the wintery grey; he tells himself he needed none of that to explain what he had. +

Yoongi tries to put the memory of him down on paper: this beaming, radiant boy that he’s lucky enough to call his own, but he ends up only being able to write down one word over and over again in the margins like a mad man lost in his own mind.

Love. +

Yoongi doesn’t have a word to describe it. To describe the ecstasy Jimin gives him; the delirious happiness that he gets drunk on, the sensation of craving the taste of his lips or the texture of his skin like he was his favorite addiction. +

still trying to memorize the texture of his mouth as warmth settled throughout his bones.
Jimin has this effect on him, this rollercoaster joyride that he goes on now that he has Jimin, and nothing will ever compare to the journey he takes him through just from being himself. +

But all of it was nothing in comparison to Jimin.
To the frenzied electricity in his veins that course through his bloodstream when his fingers touch the younger’s skin; to the lingering taste of Jimin’s lips when Yoongi simply refuses to pull away, +

And Yoongi has never felt this way before. He’s felt the racing nerves like he did when he rapped in front of his first big audience and he’s felt the bashful embarrassment when he talked to cute boys and he had even felt the delirious happiness when he won an award +
Jimin has him wrapped around his finger with his bright smile and sparkling eyes, and there’s a magic in his touch that has Yoongi obeying his every command.+
One minute he’s a mess and the next he’s a pile of cheesy smiles and then he’s all soft touches before shifting into a nervous teenager on his first date all over again. +

He doesn’t know why Jimin’s voice sends his stomach into a nervous pitter-patter, and how even the younger’s silence can make his heart beat faster.
He doesn’t know why it is that his body seems to just react to Jimin the way it does. +
He doesn’t know why the mention of Jimin’s name rings in his ears as if it’s the only thing he could hear; why the very thought of Jimin makes a smile spread across his lips. +

Rationality #yoonmin #yoonminau

Yoongi could love him no more than the daisies could tell him the truth.
 
He loves me, he loves me not –
 
Jeongguk just wishes Yoongi could've loved him as much as he pretended to.

All the things he believed he could be, like all the daisy petals that floated to the sky before falling back to the dirt; broken stems were all around Jeongguk and his fingers were reeking of all the things he pulled out of the earth that were never meant to be his. +

He loves –
 
Jeongguk was a boy in a field of white-budded hopes, a boy with yellow pollen stains on his fingertips and a heart that was so ready to love; plucking petals and making dreams. +

How long do you think it'll take before Jeongguk just shatters?
It wasn't supposed to be like this, it wasn't supposed to be broken pieces on the floor, it wasn't supposed to be a boy with the world in his eyes and the boy with nothing but his own reflection in his eyes +

He doesn't want to let Jeongguk go – I can't break his heart – but he doesn't realize he's draining everything inside of Jeongguk by keeping him close. Doesn’t realize that Jeongguk’s started breaking ever since he started holding him all wrong. +

For the things Yoongi so selfishly takes.
 
He loves me, he loves me not –
Yoongi swears he will one day, he'll love Jeongguk back, he will – but he can't force himself to feel something so deep with someone when he's still wading through the shallows, trying to make up his mind+

For how Jeongguk’s touch is warm but never enough to thaw the ice walls Yoongi’s forgotten he's built.
He uses him as a last resort beer bottle when he needs some numbing. When he needs some loving. Uses Jeongguk for all the things he so selflessly gives to Yoongi +

He has Jeongguk. He has him for all the sleepless nights and Yoongi and Jeongguk might not fit right but at least Jeongguk can fill up the space.
He loves him for all the soft words that are so sweet but never quite right. +

He loves me not, he loves me not –
 
And it's bad enough that Yoongi can't even love Jeongguk beyond an I wish I could, but he can't even let him go; selfishly spending Jeongguk’s love on the nights he's afraid of being alone the most. +

he tried to kiss Jeongguk’s lips and feel sparks instead of his own chapped mouth that his lies keep slipping through, he tried to hold him close and have Jeongguk fit into him but he can't help but to feel like he's just pulling him down farther. +

I tried.
He tried to love Jeongguk, he really did – he tried to love the younger and see more than just reflections in the light of all the deceit Jeongguk can't see with his doe eyes +

Yoongi is stealing away his love like a crook that was too ashamed to earn it for himself – “what did I ever do to deserve you?” – and Yoongi doesn't know how to return his own love to Jeongguk when he has nothing at all.
At least, nothing for Jeongguk. +

He loves me, he loves me –
 
And it's so easy for Jeongguk to forget he’s suffocating with Yoongi’s soft lips that could fool him into believing he was just breathing in again. +

He has Jeongguk sinking deeper, deeper into the lies he let him believe; weaving beliefs in his mind of something when Yoongi was only ever a boy too afraid to lose sight of what he knew. Too afraid to chase the tails of something that could've been great. +

If Jeongguk is spring with the budding flowers that remember how to live again, then Yoongi is the constant showers that have Jeongguk waiting, praying, believing that he's something he needs to bloom again.
But Yoongi only ever let him drown. +

It's not his fault he can't love Jeongguk like he thought he could. Like he should.
 
He loves me, he loves me not –
He really thought he could.
Yoongi saw Jeongguk, saw this boy – this beautiful boy with spring in his touch that made him believe he could start over +

-
It's a little cruel, don't you think?
To have Jeongguk strung along like this, to have him fall so hard when Yoongi’s still standing at the shoreline, deciding, barely even dipping his toes in.
It's not his fault though, oh no +

No, that's not entirely true – Yoongi's not completely lying.
He does love Jeongguk – he does love him like all those beautiful, fanciful metaphors that he so swoons me with.
You see, you see –
Yoongi loves Jeongguk like something that could never quite love him back. +

It's all so beautifully poetic, the metaphors he spins with sugar-laced words from pink lips of poison, and if we're being poetic, Yoongi has him in his web of lies like a butterfly who's too busy looking through the spaces to realize it's been caught the whole entire time. +

in all the guilt for all the things he's stolen from Jeongguk’s outstretched hands to him.
But he says it back, Yoongi says the words back though –
I love you like the moon loves the stars. I love you like spring loves the sun. I love you like the wind loves the sky. +

-
How long do you think he can keep up this charade?
I love you.
Jeongguk says the words – those three beautifully, sincerely heartbreaking words – with a wonder in his eyes that'll always drown Yoongi in all the things he offers him, in all the things he can't give back +

So when someone asks for a love story of Jeongguk and Taehyung –
The two will say nothing.
And that will be exactly what it is.

Once upon a time, Taehyung loved Jeongguk.
Once upon a time, Jeongguk loved him back.
(correction – if Taehyung loved him, Jeongguk could've loved him back, they were almost a happily-ever-after to a once-upon-a-time) +

It is a story of regret, dust-covered ideas that never came to life; blank pages with smudged ink of all the things they never said, of all the love that went to waste.
Once upon a time… +
It's a symphony of almosts – all the ends that were supposed to be theirs, things they never claimed. +
It's dotted with could'ves – all the roads that were meant for the two of the, footprints they never made. +

-
The story of Taehyung and Jeongguk is one that doesn't exist.
It consists of ifs – all the paths they should've taken, signs they should've read clearer. +

And that's just it – a not quite, a nearly, potential that they let flicker away, love that they let die before it even began.
Having nothing would hurt less than having an almost. +

(and Jeongguk supposes some things aren't meant to be – but sometimes we just make it that way)
Jeongguk almost loved Taehyung, and Taehyung almost loved him back. +

They were almost enough for each other.
(Jeongguk is too little now and Taehyung’s too much at this point and they can't balance without falling off)
They were almost in love and it's the saddest thing because it's the thought of being so close yet still falling short. +

There were almost sparks; eyes that almost met at the right time, words that were almost enough.
Taehyung was almost in his heart, inching his way there until Jeongguk shunned him out; he was almost in Taehyung’s thoughts, slowly invading his mind until he pushed him away. +

-
They were an almost.
Jeongguk’s skin almost met his in a moment of fingertips that were close enough to meet, his lips almost close enough to touch Taehyung’s if he took a step; if he took a chance. +

They could've had everything, but not quite, not quite –
Almost, though. +

Jeongguk could've been his reminder just one more chance.
(It's too late for you, for me – it's too late for an us)
Taehyung was the boy he used to dream about, and Jeongguk was the boy he once wanted; they could've been perfect with each other. +

Taehyung could've been his world to live for and Jeongguk could've been his lifeline to hold on to; Jeongguk could've been his redemption and Taehyung could've been his savior.
Taehyung could've been his reason for just one more night.
(I just need someone – I just need you) +

Taehyung could've been the reassurance and Jeongguk could've been the guidance; he could've been Jeongguk’s map to find himself again and he could've been Taehyung’s compass to lead him back home.
(back to Jeongguk) +

-
They could've had something.
Taehyung could've had someone to guide him down the right path that he's so far away from now; Jeongguk could've had someone to save him on those lonely nights that he almost didn't make it through. +

if he had read Taehyung’s silence right, if Taehyung had said the right words.
(‘I want you’ doesn't mean the same when he's said it to ten others before Jeongguk)
If Jeongguk’s edges were softer, if his eyes were clearer; if he and Taehyung weren't so late –
Then they could've.+

If Jeongguk were kinder – he had his heart broken one too many times by then – if Taehyung was less brash – he had his heart locked up too far by then – then maybe –
If Jeongguk could turn back the clock, if Taehyung could give him more time; +

If Jeongguk had met Taehyung before he was who he is now, before Taehyung was who he is today; before Jeongguk was as cracked as he is, before Taehyung made all his mistakes.
(perhaps Taehyung’s greatest wrong was never having him) +

-
‘If he was capable of feeling the word, he would've loved him.’
If Taehyung had known Jeongguk sooner; if Jeongguk had gone out instead of stayed in that one day, if Taehyung had taken his regular path instead of his spontaneous detour  +

Let me tell you a story about all the things that could've been; a story of Jeongguk and Taehyung that doesn't exist.
It only needs three words.
If.
Could've.
Almost. +
Rewind the clock; the fairy godmother is late and the huntsman shows no mercy, the prince rides on by with a princess, and the lover has nothing to trade for a moment of flawed bliss. +

A story where your voice wasn't enough to make him love you again; I’ll tell you a story where the rose wilts and the rain washes all his chances away.
A story about all the things that were close to a happily ever after, but not quite. +

-
Let me tell you a story.
Let me tell you a story about the shoe that didn't fit, the kiss that didn't wake sleep, the poison that killed, the curse that was eternal – I’ll tell you a story about the prince who was too lost to find his love again +

Our Story #taekook #taekookau

And here is what they don’t tell you in love stories: 
It’s just as easy for you to fall in love with someone as it is for them to fall out of love with you.  
Don’t forget.

But the worst part is, he’s not. 
And the only apology he has is one for not being enough. 
For always loving more than they loved him.

And Jeongguk is sorry he loved too much; he’s sorry he smothered sparks of something bright into deadened smoke of something that simply died, he’s sorry he let himself believe that he was meant to be loved by someone like Taehyung, he’s sorry he even tried –

how does it feel to know that everything you gave, everything you had – is meaningless enough for them to simply throw away? 
To know that you became meaningless enough for them to simply throw away? 
“I’m sorry.”

How does it feel when you see someone falling out of love with you right before your eyes? 
How does it feel to know that everything you ever shared – late nights of ‘it’ll only ever just be you and I’ and planning futures that you believed you could have;

He hates how he could never let go of the pain while all the love managed to slip away. 
And he hates how Taehyung is now one of them too.

And Jeongguk hates how he’s used that word for every person who walked away, for every person who thought he wasn’t enough to stay; how he’s left them all with claw marks that they pried themselves away from.

Jeongguk wanted him to be his reason to believe that good things happened for a reason too. 
He wanted Taehyung to prove that all that heartbreak – all that pain – was worth it. 
“Please….”

And Jeongguk remembers how he saw Taehyung for the first time and thought ‘oh no’, how Taehyung whispered against his lips if he could kiss him just before they did for the first time and how he wished ‘please let this be my last first kiss’; Jeongguk wanted it to be Taehyung.

But Taehyung has a smile that could make him walk off a cliff believing he’d be at the bottom to catch him; but Taehyung was the first and only one who made Jeongguk wholeheartedly believe that maybe – just maybe – love could be something for him too.

Jeongguk can trust himself to fall, he can trust in his naivety; he can trust that words of ‘I’ll never leave’ won’t catch him, that his heart is made up of scars from the accumulation of scratched knees with all the times he’s fallen for beautiful boys who didn’t love him back.

People change their hearts like they change house keys and one day you won’t be able to come back to the home you’ve so carefully made. 
Hasn’t Jeongguk learned anything from his heartbreak? 
“You can trust me.”

Does Jeongguk believe in happily-ever-afters? 
At this point, really – he deserved it if he was stupid enough to believe, to even hope that when someone promised forever, when they said /always/, they’d mean it. 
Shouldn’t he know by now that people change their minds?

And what do you do when you love too much when you’re barely enough? 
/You’re everything I want, you’re everything I need/
And Jeongguk swore, he swore-he told himself that someone would come along one day, someone would /stay/ one day– 
And he let himself believe it would be Tae

Jeongguk supposes he has a way of making the word love seem so sour; all the lovers in the past handing him off saying ‘someone will love you better than me’ but he knew better than that, he knew they didn’t want his love as their responsibility. 
Where does it go?
Jeongguk doesn’t know if Taehyung means his love is silly or if Jeongguk was for believing in Taehyung’s love for him and he doesn’t realize until the morning that he never said yes.

And Taehyung says "of course, babe, don’t be silly" with a kiss on the lips and an answer in his eyes that pierces right through Jeongguk. 
And he says "don’t ask silly questions" before he turns the other way.

how he remembers Jeongguk as an afterthought and how he is diminished, closer and closer to nothing in Taehyung’s eyes. 
How Taehyung doesn’t love him anymore. 
"Do you love me?" he asks.

How he grows, better without Jeongguk. 
And of course Jeongguk sees it – how the only smile of Taehyung’s that he sees are ones when he’s turned away from him, how Taehyung says his name like a stranger instead of the lover that used to entwine it with his own;

He sees how Jeongguk’s kisses don’t taste so sweet anymore, how he doesn’t like how Jeongguk looks in his arms anymore, how he outgrows Jeongguk like clothes that another him used to wear – how suddenly, Jeongguk isn’t enough for him.
And then Taehyung sees.

But that’s the thing about interest, you see – Jeongguk couldn’t pay him back. 
He couldn’t pay him back and Taehyung’s love for him grew while the younger fell flat, realizing that all he was being given – realizing all he couldn’t give back. 
Jeongguk tried, he /tried/.

With the interest accumulating – Taehyung looks at Jeongguk and thinks this is what I want, we’ll grow into something bigger one day, this is love – Taehyung looks at Jeongguk every day with brighter eyes, and he loves him every day with more of his heart.
All the nose brushes and forehead kisses, all the softest caresses and sweetest words – every I love you and every forever cost more than what he could give back in return.

Jeongguk supposes he had it coming, really. 
It was too good – too perfect – and he was too happy and God knows happiness doesn’t come without a price. 
And oh, Jeongguk paid the price

How every touch is a compression that says please bring them back to me; how they drown at the sight of you, how you suffocate them so.

hi !! thank you for reading my little random thoughts on our boys :) here are my links if you want to check out some more of my writing or if you want to support me on ko-fi !! have a great day🤍 https://t.co/SNuxPVeK9S
He’s the comfort of a warm hug that takes away some of the lingering pain and the taste of chamomile tea before bed that slowly causes your mind to rest.

He’s the reminder that you’ll never have to do any of your bad days over again and tomorrow is a fresh start. Jungkook is the comfort of feeling valid in your emotions and the soothing nature of finally figuring something out or clocking out after an endless shift.

Overall, Jungkook is the comfort of finally releasing everything held inside. He’s the feeling of relaxing your shoulders and letting out a sigh of relief when you find a file you thought you accidentally deleted.
He would keep an eye out for you to make sure you don’t get upset again but he wouldnt want to make you feel suffocated by him bugging you and constantly being around you.

Jungkook would also check in on you regularly to see how you’re doing after a bad day, but he would do so by sending you dumb memes and photos of himself with silly captions (‘Das not good’ is his personal favorite).
“You walked out of your room and to the couch before 2 pm today! You ate good meals! You turned on the TV! I’m so proud of you for even doing those things when it must’ve been a struggle.”
Congrats! You’ve unlocked determined Koo who will try whatever he can to make you feel like it’s okay to have those days.

Jungkook definitely has blanket fort supplies at the ready when you don’t feel like doing anything or just lack the energy to even try and let things out. Maybe there’s nothing to really let out at all, you just don’t feel like it today.

He gets a little panicked himself when he sees you at your lowest points and he knows he might not say things that are actually helpful, so he tries to help you come back down a little before talking through everything.
Jungkook is also the person who would bring you coloring books and plenty of art supplies or go with you to a dance studio or music room if you want to let out everything in a less physical way.

Jungkook is the friend that hands you a pillow to scream into, takes you outside, and tells you to throw something in anger, or even just takes you to the gym to let it out on a punching bag for a bit.

Jungkook is the freedom of expressing yourself. He might not be the best and talking through everything that’s bothering you in the moment but you better believe he’ll help you find a way to express those emotions instead of holding them all in.
Jungkook: https://t.co/K9m6nzt01P

He’s soft, comfort song playlists that a friend makes for you, saying every song reminds them of you. Taehyung is the comfort of heartwarming care that surprises you at the very moments when you think you’re about to break.

Overall, Taehyung is the comfort of being cared for and looked after. He’s the feeling of appreciation and shy smiles of thanks when someone does something kind for you. He’s the look of surprise you get when someone remembers something seemingly insignificant about you.
He’s one of those rare people that you can feel completely comfortable with while you’re both on opposite ends of the couch doing your own things.

Taehyung would also definitely bring you all your favorites foods and snacks as well, and say hello to another face mask buddy because he’s ready to get comfy and attach himself to your side. Taehyung is the comfort of quiet and solitude.

If you’re a little too tired and worn out from being yourself and handling everything that comes with being you, don’t worry !! Taehyung is on his way now with multiple wigs, sunglasses, and outfits so you both can be someone else for the night.
I see Taehyung as the comfort of laying in bed late at night with your favorite playlist flowing through your headphones. He’s the comfort of playing dress-up too.

Taehyung would see you being quiet and seemingly trapped inside your head and take you on a drive with calm, lo-fi music playing through the speakers. He wouldnt talk until you do because he wants you to at least feel at ease physically if you can’t mentally or emotionally.

Taehyung notices all the little things but he respects your boundaries.

“I saw on your calendar in your room you had a test today so breakfast is on me! We can’t have you take a test on an empty stomach, so tell me when you’re ready, and I’ll come over with your usual.”

Taehyung is the comfort of being cared for. He’s the person that observes more than most people realize, so don’t be surprised when he texts you little reminders or comes over to your place with some groceries you forgot you were running out of.
